%h2 Maybe Disable UEFI

%p The main idea of this section is that when my laptop boots up, I can access UEFI.

%p And, after I access UEFI, I probably want to disable it.

%p I offer more discussion below.

%p  Modern laptops have a software feature named UEFI which supports another feature called "Secure Boot".

%p If you are curious about UEFI, it is easy to find information about it:

%p
  %a(href='https://www.google.com/search?q=What+is+UEFI' target='x')
    https://www.google.com/search?q=What+is+UEFI

%p Personally, I am not curious about UEFI; I usually want to disable it because it often interferes with Ubuntu.

%p Sometimes Ubuntu works fine when UEFI is enabled, but my experience is that UEFI usually prevents me from installing Ubuntu.

%p So, I have developed the habit of disabling UEFI.

%p Someday I will learn how to install Ubuntu on a UEFI-laptop.

%p Currently my practice is to try to install and operate Ubuntu on a new UEFI-laptop.

%p If it works, great, if not I disaable UEFI and move on.

%p Disabling UEFI is not very difficult but it is not as easy as clicking a checkbox.

%p I disable UEFI by interacting with software called the BIOS.

%p One problem with BIOS software is that the UI is different depending on the laptop.

%p An HP laptop will have different BIOS than a Dell laptop.

%p Usually though, the BIOS UI is simple.

%p It is a small hierarchy of pages which allow me to set BIOS options.

%p The most important option is UEFI; I want to disable UEFI.

%p Another option I sometimes see is "Legacy" support which I see as the opposite of UEFI.

%p If I see Legacy support I always enable it (which can be tricky sometimes because I may need to disable UEFI first).

%p Another option I like to enable is "Virtualization" which will allow my laptop to run software like Virtualbox and VMWare.

%p Sometimes it is difficult to access the BIOS UI.

%p For me it is usually a trial-error process of systematically trying each F-key at the top of the keyboard during bootup.

%p Sometimes google is useful.

%p For example if you have a Dell Inspiron 17 5000 laptop you could try these queries:

%ul
