%p From the above query I could learn that I access the BIOS by holding down F2 during bootup.

%p Also I see that F12 will give me access to "one-time boot menu".

%p I can use this menu to force my Laptop to boot from a DVD or USB-stick rather than hard-drive which is useful if the hard-drive contains a copy of windows-10 which I hope to eventually over-write with Ubuntu.

%hr/

%h2 Initial Bootup (DVD)

%p The next step in the Ubuntu installation process is: "Initial Bootup".

%p If I bootup off of DVD, assuming my laptop has a DVD drive, here is how I describe it:

%ul
  %li Put the DVD in the tray and close the tray.
  %li Power off the laptop
  %li Power on  the laptop

%p If I am lucky, the laptop will "see" the DVD and boot off of the DVD rather than the hard-drive.

%p If I am not lucky, I will need to force the laptop to boot off the DVD.

%p Many laptops allow me to make this happen.

%p My Dell laptop for example allows me to hold down the F12 key during power-up.

%p Then during that sequence, the laptop will serve me a UI I can use to force the laptop to boot off the DVD.

%p Usually I can get more information about this process from both Youtube and Google.

